# Solution Regex:
Use Regex to find all matches of an `expression` or &quot;conditional clause&quot; in a String. The following regular Expression will match against any character sequences

## Statement
In short, the full statement, you have to match against looks like this:

    (100|200);ABC;(AAA|BBB)(?:(?!(CCC|DDD))).$

### Explanation
 - `(100|200)` -&gt; beginning either with &#39;100&#39; or &#39;200&#39;
 - `;` -&gt; followed by a &#39;;&#39; as a delimeter
 - `ABC` -&gt; followed by the character group &#39;ABC&#39;
 - `;` -&gt; followed again by the delimiter
 - `(AAA|BBB)` -&gt; followed by either &#39;AAA&#39; or &#39;BBB&#39;

The next part of the expression seems a little cryptic, so here comes a more detailed explanation:

 - `(?:` -&gt; marks the beginning of a non capturing group
 - `(?!` -&gt; negative lookahead (Asserts that the following Regex does not match)
 - `(CCC|DDD)` -&gt; matches to Strings &#39;CCC&#39; and &#39;DDD&#39; (referred to, by the negative lookahead)
 - `))` -&gt; end of the non capturing group and negative lookahead
 - `.` -&gt; matches any character (except for line terminators) might have to be changed into the delimiter `;` for a more specific query or removed entirely based on what your data actually looks like and what you want
 - `$` -&gt; matches the end of a line

# Implementation
## Python:
Python enables you to easily evaluate Regular Expressions using the library `re`. It should already be a part of the Vanilla version of `python3`:

    import re
    
    my_string = &#39;|100;ABC;AAA;
    |100;ABC;BBB;
    |200;ABC;AAA;
    |200;ABC;AAA&#39;
    my_expression = &#39;(100|200);ABC;(AAA|BBB)(?:(?!(CCC|DDD))).$&#39;
    
    
    res = re.findall(my_expression, my_string)
    print([r for r in res])

## Java
However Java can do Regex operations as well:

    import java.util.regex.*;
    try {
        Pattern regex = Pattern.compile(&quot;(100|200);ABC;(AAA|BBB)(?:(?!(CCC|DDD))).$&quot;);
        Matcher regexMatcher = regex.matcher(subjectString);
        while (regexMatcher.find()) {
            for (int i = 1; i &lt;= regexMatcher.groupCount(); i++) {
                // matched text: regexMatcher.group(i)
                // match start: regexMatcher.start(i)
                // match end: regexMatcher.end(i)
            }
        } 
    } catch (PatternSyntaxException ex) {
        // Syntax error in the regular expression
    }
### Testing
You can easily test and develop regular expressions on [this website][1]. It makes it easy to learn the expressions since every element of your expression will be explained on the side. You can run it against your own custom Strings.


  [1]: https://regex101.com

